 Mengel Company; Louisville, KY; 1953.","resource_description":"The earliest closets (from the Latin <em>clausum<\/em> for &lsquo;closed&rsquo;) were small, private rooms in the home used by the wealthy to enjoy books or art in solitude. Even the rich had few possessions prior to the 18th century so clothes and personal effects were most often stored in wardrobes, chests or clothespresses. It was around that time that closets, in roughly their modern, built-in form, began first appearing, though they were usually located near the fireplace and reserved for general storage.<a href=&quot;#fn46\&quot; id=\"ref46\">46<\/a><br \/>\nFollowing World War II, largely in response to the increase in wealth and consumption that defined the postwar middle class, larger and deeper sized closets began to be built in new home construction. For the first time, most people had more stuff than they had space and henceforth storage in the home would forever be &ldquo;defined primarily as the need for the well-ordered accommodation of commodity excess.&rdquo;<a href=&quot;#fn47\&quot; id=\"ref47\">47<\/a>  Furthermore, storage also began figuring into property values, with the Federal Housing Authority opining that &ldquo;provision for storage is a most important element in determining the desirability of the property to prospective purchasers.&rdquo;<a href=&quot;#fn48\&quot; id=\"ref48\">48<\/a><br \/>\n<br \/>\n<br \/>\n<br \/>\n46. Mary Miley Theobald, &ldquo;Myths That Should by Now Be History,&rdquo; http:\/\/www.history.org\/Foundation\/journal\/Winter08\/stuff.cfm <a href=&quot;#ref46\&quot; title=\"Jump back to footnote 46 in the text.\">\u21a9<\/a> <br \/>\n47. Diane Harris, <em>Little White Houses: How the Postwar Home Constructed Race in America<\/em> (Minneapolis : University of Minnesota Press, [2013]), 187.<a href=&quot;#ref47\&quot; title=\"Jump back to footnote 47 in the text.\">\u21a9<\/a> <br \/>\n48. Ibid.<a href=&quot;#ref48\&quot; title=\"Jump back to footnote 48 in the text.\">\u21a9<\/a>","resource_full_text":"","resource_types_for_resource_id":"Archival Material","resource_asset_type":"10","resource_image_thumbnail":"..\/images\/Rsrc_TN_003551.jpg","resource_asset_type_label":"","resource_file_size":"0.0 kB","resource_file_size_unformatted":"230.357421875","resource_grade_level":"","resource_curriculum":"","resource_tour":"","resource_file_time":"00m 00s","resource_file_time_unformatted":"0","resource_source_detail":"\"Tools of the Trade: 19th- and 20th-Century Architectural Trade Catalogs,\" Case 7, Ryerson &amp; Burnham Libraries, August 4, 2015-October 12, 2015.<br \/>\n<br \/>\n<a href=&quot;https:\/\/digital-libraries.artic.edu\/cdm\/ref\/collection\/mqc\/id\/68837&quot;>Link to R&amp;B Archives Digital Collections record<\/a>","resource_tags_for_resource_id":"architecture"}};
        
    (function($){
		$(document).ready(function(){
		    $("#reset").hide();
		    var galleryContent = $("#galleryContent"), gCEnd = galleryContent.children(".floatClear");
		    var types = new Array();
		    		    
		    $.each(galleryObjects, function(i, gObj) {
		        (function() {
		            types.push(gObj.resource_types_for_resource_id);
    				// build DOM objects and nest them through appends
    				var g = $('<div>', { 'class': 'galleryImage' } );
    				var gLink = $( '<a>', { 'href': gObj.resource_link } );
    				var gThumbnail = $( '<img src="' + gObj.resource_image_thumbnail + '" class="scaled" />' );
    				var gTooltip = $( "<div>", { "class": "tooltip", "html": '<img src="' + gObj.resource_image_thumbnail +'" alt="'+ gObj.resource_title +'" /><div id="artworkData"><strong>'+ gObj.resource_title +'</strong></div>' } );
    				gLink.append(gThumbnail);
    				gLink.append(gTooltip);
    				g.append(gLink);
			
    				// associate object to DOM object
    				g.artData = gObj;
				
    				// bind filtering events
    				g.bind( "filterByType", function(event,type) {
    					if ( $.inArray( type, $.map(g.artData.resource_types_for_resource_id.split(","), function(n){ return $.trim(n); }) ) == -1 ) { g.hide(); }
    					else { g.fadeIn(); }
    				});
    				
    				g.bind( "filterByTag", function(event,tag) {
    					if ( $.inArray( tag, $.map(g.artData.resource_tags_for_resource_id.split(","), function(n){ return $.trim(n); }) ) == -1 ) { g.hide(); }
    					else { g.fadeIn(); }
    				});
    				
    				g.bind( "filterReset", function(event){
    				    g.fadeIn();
    				});
			
    				// stolen from tooltip js
    				gTooltip.hide();		
    				// do rollovers for this link -- you can change the fadeIn and fadeOut to just show() and hide() if you don't like the fading effect
    				gLink.hover(
    				    function () {
        				    gTooltip.show();
        				    // position tooltip
            				gTooltip.css( { "bottom": gThumbnail.height()/2 + ( g.height() - gThumbnail.height() ) + "px", "left": gThumbnail.width()/2 + "px" } );
            			},
        			
        				function () { gTooltip.hide(); }
    				);
    				// end steal
			
    				// insert this gallery node before end of list
    				gCEnd.before(g);
			    })();
            });
            
            			
						
			//event resetting all filters
			$( "#reset a").click( function () {
			    $(".galleryImage").trigger( "filterReset" );
			    $("#count").text($('.galleryImage :visible').size());
			    $(".active").removeClass("active");
			    $("#reset").hide();
				return false;
			});
			
			$(".galleryImage img.scaled").each( function (index) {
                var img = $(this);
                var max = 112;
                // fix dimensions
                if ( img.height() > img.width() ){
                    img.css( { "height":max, "width":"auto"} );
                }
                else { img.css( { "height":"auto", "width":max} ); }
            });
		});
	})(jQuery);
</script> </div>
